  <p class="section-label">About</p>
  <img src="/ben-portrait.png" alt="Ben Caddy" class="portrait" />
  <h2 class="section-headline">The long way round</h2>
  <div class="body-copy">
    <p>I&rsquo;m an entrepreneur and writer based in the UK. From Bristol, through Cape Town, C&ocirc;te d&rsquo;Ivoire, Bahrain, Dubai, Bangkok, California, now Bristol again. Thirty years of standing in different rooms and watching people try to make meaning out of what&rsquo;s in front of them.</p>
    <p>That work has mostly been commercial. I built an agency in the Middle East that scaled to fifty-odd people and served some of the world&rsquo;s biggest brands. I ran a live events company that delivered cultural events at a scale that changed what people in that region thought events could be. I&rsquo;ve advised the smallest startups to the United Nations, and spent the back half of my career helping founders and owners see what they couldn&rsquo;t see from inside their own thing.</p>
    <p>I currently work with a diverse portfolio of clients, am co-founder of a game studio creating collaborative storytelling products for education, and am active in helping create career pathways for young people from underserved communities.</p>
    <p>Most of it has come down to the same instinct: stand at enough angles, and from far enough away, that the thing starts to look weird.</p>
  </div>

  <blockquote class="pull-quote">&ldquo;Then find the story the situation is actually telling, so you can find the one it needs.&rdquo;</blockquote>

  <div class="body-copy">
    <p>Now I write about that instinct: the way story runs underneath everything we think we&rsquo;re choosing, and what it costs us not to notice.</p>
  </div>
</section>
